Neil Nitin Mukesh is a highly talented and highly underrated actor. 
Many years ago at some awards show, as he was sitting innocently in the audience, he found himself being ridiculed by Saif Ali Khan and Shahrukh Khan (who else) as they mocked him over his, of all things, "surname". They said, with pompous pride, standing on the podium, that we both have proper last names like "Khan", so why do you have a 'first name' as your last name? They just, out of the blue, blatantly picked on his name, in public. It was cringeworthy for anyone watching. NNM, poor guy was nonplussed. 
I would like to tell those ignorant "Khan" bozos that in several states of our country, the first name of the father becomes the last name of the son. Try traveling South.
Neil should have answered, "I do it to respect my ancestors. You keep a generic last name because you are probably embarrassed by yours". 
After all, Neil's grandfather contributed immensely to India's cultural landscape. He did so by the sheer dint of hard work and immense talent, for which he earned the adulation, admiration and respect of an entire grateful nation. When Mukesh died, Raj Kapoor said sorrowfully, "I've lost my voice". Mukesh's songs are evergreen and legendary. Saif's ancestry, apart from his father who we all respect.... their main claim to fame is money. Rich nawabs of an impoverished India. Money they inherited, not earned. Obviously not all the money in the world will buy you etiquette. And I'm not in the least interested in knowing what SRK's ancestors were all about. Couldn't have been about manners and decency, because those aren't traits they passed on to him. This was painfully evident on the stage that day.
